# (b) LP Model with External Storage

---

## Decision Variables

\[
x_{it} \ge 0 \quad \text{production of product } i \text{ in month } t
\]

\[
I_{it} \ge 0 \quad \text{end-of-month inventory}
\]

\[
V_t^{in} \ge 0 \quad \text{internal storage volume used}
\]

\[
V_t^{out} \ge 0 \quad \text{external storage volume used}
\]

---

## Inventory Balance

For all \( i,t \):

\[
I_{i,t-1} + x_{it} - d_{it} = I_{it}
\]

with:

\[
I_{i0} = 0
\]

---

## Production Capacity

\[
x_{1t} + x_{2t} \le 120000 \quad \forall t
\]

---

## Storage Volume Definition

\[
0.2 I_{1t} + 0.4 I_{2t} = V_t^{in} + V_t^{out}
\]

---

## Internal Warehouse Capacity

\[
V_t^{in} \le 15000 \quad \forall t
\]

---

## Objective Function

Minimize total production + storage cost:

\[
\min \sum_{t=1}^{12} \left(
\sum_{i=1}^{2} c_{it} x_{it}
+ 1 \cdot V_t^{in}
+ 1.5 \cdot V_t^{out}
\right)
\]

---

## Nonnegativity

\[
x_{it}, I_{it}, V_t^{in}, V_t^{out} \ge 0
\]

---

\[
\boxed{\text{This is the required linear programming model.}}
\]
【验证之后的模型】:
 ### ✅ Model Verification and Corrections

The previous model is **almost correct**, but two improvements are required:

1. **End-of-horizon inventory condition missing**  
   Since the problem is for one year and only requires meeting demand, we should impose:
   \[
   I_{i,12} = 0
   \]
   Otherwise, the model may overproduce in December and leave unnecessary inventory.

2. **Internal/external warehouse allocation modeling can be simplified**  
   Because internal storage is cheaper (1 < 1.5), the optimizer will always use internal capacity first automatically.  
   The current split-variable modeling is correct and linear, so it does **not require binary variables**.  
   It is already efficient and clean.  

No structural errors exist.  
