  To ensure the normal operation of a certain piece of equipment, it is necessary to keep three types of spare parts: \mathbf{E}_1, \mathbf{E}_2, \mathbf{E}_3. Increasing the number of spare parts can improve the reliability of the equipment’s operation, but also increases the cost, and the total investment is limited to 8,000 yuan. The relationship between the number of spare parts, the increased reliability, and the costs is shown in Table 7-10.  

  Table 7-10  


  <html><body><table><tr><td rowspan="2">Number of Spares</td><td colspan="3">Increase in Reliability</td><td colspan="3">Cost (thousand yuan)</td></tr><tr><td>E1</td><td>E2</td><td>E3</td><td>E1</td><td>E2</td><td>E3</td></tr><tr><td>z=1</td><td>0.3</td><td>0.2</td><td>0.1</td><td>1</td><td>3</td><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>z=2</td><td>0.4</td><td>0.5</td><td>0.2</td><td>2</td><td>5</td><td>3</td></tr><tr><td>z=3</td><td>0.5</td><td>0.9</td><td>0.7</td><td>3</td><td>6</td><td>4</td></tr></table></body></html>  

  Question:Under the constraint of not exceeding the investment limit, and aiming to maximize the reliability of the equipment’s operation, what is the optimal number of spares for each type of part?  


-------------
【数学模型】:
 ### Decision Variables  

Let  

\[
x_{ij} =
\begin{cases}
1, & \text{if for spare part } E_i \text{ we choose level } j \ (j=1,2,3) \\
0, & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

where  
- \(i = 1,2,3\) corresponds to spare parts \(E_1, E_2, E_3\),  
- \(j = 1,2,3\) corresponds to number of spares \(z=1,2,3\).  

---

### Parameters  

**Reliability increase** \(r_{ij}\):

\[
\begin{aligned}
&r_{11}=0.3,\quad r_{12}=0.4,\quad r_{13}=0.5 \\
&r_{21}=0.2,\quad r_{22}=0.5,\quad r_{23}=0.9 \\
&r_{31}=0.1,\quad r_{32}=0.2,\quad r_{33}=0.7
\end{aligned}
\]

**Cost (thousand yuan)** \(c_{ij}\):

\[
\begin{aligned}
&c_{11}=1,\quad c_{12}=2,\quad c_{13}=3 \\
&c_{21}=3,\quad c_{22}=5,\quad c_{23}=6 \\
&c_{31}=2,\quad c_{32}=3,\quad c_{33}=4
\end{aligned}
\]

Budget limit:

\[
B = 8
\]

---

### Mathematical Model  

#### Objective Function  

Maximize total reliability increase:

\[
\max Z =
\sum_{i=1}^{3} \sum_{j=1}^{3} r_{ij} x_{ij}
\]

Explicitly:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\max Z = 
&0.3x_{11}+0.4x_{12}+0.5x_{13} \\
&+0.2x_{21}+0.5x_{22}+0.9x_{23} \\
&+0.1x_{31}+0.2x_{32}+0.7x_{33}
\end{aligned}
\]

---

#### Budget Constraint  

\[
\sum_{i=1}^{3} \sum_{j=1}^{3} c_{ij} x_{ij} \le 8
\]

Explicitly:

\[
\begin{aligned}
&1x_{11}+2x_{12}+3x_{13} \\
&+3x_{21}+5x_{22}+6x_{23} \\
&+2x_{31}+3x_{32}+4x_{33}
\le 8
\end{aligned}
\]

---

#### Selection Constraints  

For each spare part, select **at most one level**:

\[
\sum_{j=1}^{3} x_{ij} \le 1 \qquad i=1,2,3
\]

That is,

\[
\begin{aligned}
x_{11}+x_{12}+x_{13} &\le 1 \\
x_{21}+x_{22}+x_{23} &\le 1 \\
x_{31}+x_{32}+x_{33} &\le 1
\end{aligned}
\]

---

#### Binary Constraints  

\[
x_{ij} \in \{0,1\}, \qquad i=1,2,3;\ j=1,2,3
\]

