# ✅ Optimized Mathematical Model

---

### Decision Variables

Let  

\[
x_i = \text{number of patrol units assigned to warehouse } i
\]

where  

\[
x_i \in \{2,3,4\}, \quad i=1,2,3,4
\]

---

### Objective Function

Minimize total expected accidents:

\[
\min Z = f_1(x_1) + f_2(x_2) + f_3(x_3) + f_4(x_4)
\]

where

\[
\begin{aligned}
f_1(2)=18,\; f_1(3)=16,\; f_1(4)=12 \\
f_2(2)=38,\; f_2(3)=36,\; f_2(4)=30 \\
f_3(2)=14,\; f_3(3)=12,\; f_3(4)=11 \\
f_4(2)=34,\; f_4(3)=31,\; f_4(4)=25
\end{aligned}
\]

---

### Constraints

#### 1. Total patrol units constraint

\[
x_1 + x_2 + x_3 + x_4 = 12
\]

#### 2. Bounds

\[
2 \le x_i \le 4, \quad i=1,2,3,4
\]

\[
x_i \in \mathbb{Z}
\]

---

# ✅ Final Compact Model

\[
\boxed{
\begin{aligned}
\min \quad & \sum_{i=1}^{4} f_i(x_i) \\
\text{s.t.} \quad
& x_1 + x_2 + x_3 + x_4 = 12 \\
& 2 \le x_i \le 4, \quad i=1,\dots,4 \\
& x_i \in \mathbb{Z}
\end{aligned}
}
\]

---

### 🔎 Why This Version Is Better

- Uses **4 integer variables instead of 12 binary variables**
- Smaller model size
- More natural for dynamic programming
- Easier to convert into Gurobi code (can use piecewise-linear objective or table lookup)

