 The previous model contains an indexing error in the coverage logic.  
Specifically, the mapping between start day and shift worked on a given calendar day was reversed.

Below is the **corrected and simplified final integer linear programming model**.

---

# ✅ Correct Mathematical Model

## Decision Variables

\[
x_d \in \mathbb{Z}_+ \qquad d=1,\dots,7
\]

Number of nurses whose 5‑day work cycle **starts on day \( d \)**  
(\(1=\) Monday, …, \(7=\) Sunday).

Each nurse works:

Day 1 → Shift 1  
Day 2 → Shift 2  
Day 3 → Shift 3  
Day 4 → Shift 4  
Day 5 → Shift 5  
Day 6–7 → Off  

Total nurses:

\[
N = \sum_{d=1}^{7} x_d
\]

All indices below are taken **modulo 7**.

---

# Shift Coverage on Day \( t \)

A nurse starting on day \( d \) works on day \( t \) iff:

\[
t = d, d+1, d+2, d+3, d+4
\]

Thus, on calendar day \( t \):

\[
\begin{aligned}
\text{Shift 1} &: x_t \\
\text{Shift 2} &: x_{t-1} \\
\text{Shift 3} &: x_{t-2} \\
\text{Shift 4} &: x_{t-3} \\
\text{Shift 5} &: x_{t-4}
\end{aligned}
\]

---

# Time Period Coverage Requirements

### Period 1 (6:00–10:00)

Covered by Shift 1 and Shift 2:

\[
x_t + x_{t-1} \ge 18
\]

---

### Period 2 (10:00–14:00)

Covered by Shift 2 and Shift 3:

\[
x_{t-1} + x_{t-2} \ge 20
\]

---

### Period 3 (14:00–18:00)

Covered by Shift 3 and Shift 4:

\[
x_{t-2} + x_{t-3} \ge 19
\]

---

### Period 4 (18:00–22:00)

Covered by Shift 4 and Shift 5:

\[
x_{t-3} + x_{t-4} \ge 17
\]

---

### Period 5 (22:00–6:00)

Covered only by Shift 5:

\[
x_{t-4} \ge 12
\]

---

# Objective Function

\[
\min \; N = \sum_{d=1}^{7} x_d
\]

---

# Complete Final Model

\[
\min \sum_{d=1}^{7} x_d
\]

subject to, for all \( t=1,\dots,7 \) (mod 7):

\[
\begin{aligned}
x_t + x_{t-1} &\ge 18 \\
x_{t-1} + x_{t-2} &\ge 20 \\
x_{t-2} + x_{t-3} &\ge 19 \\
x_{t-3} + x_{t-4} &\ge 17 \\
x_{t-4} &\ge 12 \\
x_d &\in \mathbb{Z}_+
\end{aligned}
\]

---

# ✅ Model Validation

✔ Correct shift-to-day mapping  
✔ Correct period coverage structure  
✔ Correct weekly cyclic indexing  
✔ Minimal decision variable set (7 variables only)  
✔ Fully linear integer programming formulation  

